To use PowerPalette, you will need:

    * WB3.0
    * AGA chipset

@endnode

@node Before "Before you start...a quick word from our sponsors..."
					  @{b}Before Starting PowerPalette@{ub}

Before you run PowerPalette, you should quickly configure the ASL requester size. Here's how...

Select the PowerPalette and get its icon information. Adjust the following tooltypes:

    ASLWIDTH : Width of ASL requester (can be left as it is)
    ASLHEIGHT: Height of ASL requester (can be left as it is)

That way, the ASL requesters will look nice and centered, and reasonably sized. For a long time, programs only
allowed the user to use a naff-sized ASL requester which needed to be enlargened every time you wanted to use it.
Here's my (sort of) fix.

@endnode

@node Usage "How to use PowerPalette"
						      @{b}Usage@{ub}

PowerPalette is fairly self-explanatory, but here's a quick rundown anyway.

The palette is edited by selecting a colour register and using the RGB sliders. The cycle gadget can be used to
switch between RGB (Red, Green, Blue) and HSB (Hue, Saturation, Brightness).

By selecting a colour register and clicking Undo, that register will be reverted to its original colour. Undo All
can be used to revert ALL colours to their originals. The menu option Reset Colours works in the same way as Undo
All, only colours will be reverted to their originals even after you've opened another palette.

Reduce White reduces all RGB values of 255,255,255 to 245,245,245 automatically.

You can jump to another screen by selecting Find Screen from the menu, and selecting the name of the screen. Many
private screens have no names, but they can still be selected and jumped to.

Palettes can be loaded and saved with the relevant menu options.

To exit PowerPalette, click OK or Cancel. Closing the window with the close button will only hide it (it can be
popped up again with the hotkey), but it will still be in memory. Alternatively, Exchange can be used.

A new feature added to PowerPalette V1.01a is the ability to force-close a screen (menu Screen/Force Close). This
should ONLY be used if a program exits whilst PowerPalette is on its screen, and tries to close its screen. This
will fail, but chances are that the program won't check this and will just free everything up and leave. In this
case, it is safe to use Force Close on the screen to get rid of it. PowerPalette will then also exit.

NEVER use Force Close on any screen which a program is still using. 99% of the time, this will cause a crash. As
I say, this option is only useful when it has to be used.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes "Hammer. Saw. Chisel. Screwdriver. etc."
						    @{b}ToolTypes@{ub}

@{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}

Standard popup key. Whatever you enter in here gets passed straight to the Commodities system, so it might not be
wise to enter any old junk here.

@{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}

YES or NO. If YES, the interface will popup when the program is run. Otherwise it will be hidden.

@{b}ASLWIDTH@{ub}

Width of ASL requester in pixels.

@{b}ASLHEIGHT@{ub}

Height of ASL requester in pixels.

@endnode

@node Bugs "Have you found a bug? Let me know..."
						      @{b}Bugs@{ub}

As every programmer knows only too well, you can never iron out bugs completely. There will always be one left in
there somewhere. Unfortunately, most programmers (including me) don't have enough time to run the program day in
day out looking for bugs. So if you discover a bug, I'd be grateful if you could inform me of it so that I can
blast it away with my machine gun.

If you want to report a bug, try to include details of circumstances leading to the bug, the bug itself (in as
much detail as possible, inc. any gurus etc.), and circumstances after the bug (system stability, corrupted
graphics etc.). I also need to know what programs you are running in the background (screen blankers etc.) and
your hardware setup. If you can provide all this lot, stick it together and send it to...

>>>>> tone_20@my-Deja.com <<<<< (note the new E-Mail address)

With the subject "PowerPalette Bug". Also, before you send me a bug report, make sure that you're running the
latest version of PowerPalette (the Aminet always holds the latest version). There's no point in reporting old
bugs that have since been fixed.

Thanx a lot.

BUG FIXES
=========

V1.0

1* PowerPalette saved Prefs files with the first 8 colours. I realised recently that the WB Palette programs works
   with the first 4 colours and the last 4 colours, so I adjusted the saving method accordingly.

V1.01

2* The tooltype CX_POPUP wasn't working properly; if PowerPalette was run from WB, it automatically popped up.
   Although this was my original intention, I can see that it doesn't fit in with general Amiga style, and could
   cause problems if the program was dumped in WBStartup. CX_POPUP now works OK. (reported by Ronne Tennebekk)

3* A bug was introduced in V1.01, which appeared when you tried to save 256+ colour screens. The save would never
   end, either for WBPrefs or NPal files. Fixed. (reported by Ronne Tennebekk)

4* A whole multitude of bugs in PowerPalette, only evident when used on 256+ colour screens, were discovered. This
   was due entirely to loop variables of size UBYTE; this should've been OK, but I forgot that for() loops need to
   take the loop counter to 1 over the maximum specified size. This caused many hang-ups. All of these are now
   fixed (I hope :-).

5* The window title should show "<hotkey = blah blah>", but sometimes showed "<hotkey = blah blah<". Fixed.

@EndNode

@node About "Technical info on PowerPalette"
						      @{b}About@{ub}

PowerPalette V1.01a was developed using the following tools/programs:

	DICE 3.16 (I really should get StormC some time...)

	AmiTex (a great text editor with a few bugs)

	Enforcer V37.72 (indispensable)

	MungWall V37.71 (indispensable)

	Sushi (etc.)

The code is pretty much OS-friendly, and causes no Enforcer/Mungwall hits/reports. It should run perfectly
alongside other programs (assuming they aren't hacks; MCP being the obvious one here).

V1.01a includes a general code clean up, and update to my new programming standards. The old code was basically
bodged together, non-standard in places, and generally not very easy to understand. You should find the new code
an improvement over the original! It's still a little bit dodgy in places, but it's too late to re-code the whole
thing now.

The GUI is now sort of font-sensitive. Don't expect it to be perfect, but it works sufficiently well enough to
handle reasonably-sized fonts. PowerPalette is designed with the XHelvetica/11 font in mind, so if you have that,
use it; it'll look better.

A load of bugs have been pulled out which were introduced in V1.01. Sorry, I honestly don't know how they slipped
through the bug-testing phase.

@EndNode

